'''Yamadai Shrine''' (やまだいじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Kishiwada|Q740456|WD=Q740456|1=Kishiwada, Osaka}}, {{ill|lt=Osaka Prefecture|Q122723|WD=Q122723|1=Osaka Prefecture}}. Its honden and other structures are designated {{ill|lt=tangible cultural properties|Q2901860|WD=Q2901860|1=Tangible Cultural Property (Japan)}}.

=== History ===
In the early {{ill|lt=8th century|Q8086|WD=Q8086|1=8th century}}, in the reign of {{ill|lt=Emperor Monmu|Q357246|WD=Q357246|1=Emperor Monmu}}, a shrine hall of 7 bays was built with a small corner width of 5 {{ill|lt=ken|Q3195007|WD=Q3195007|1=Ken (unit)}}, and later in the age of {{ill|lt=Emperor Shōmu|Q349263|WD=Q349263|1=Emperor Shōmu}}, {{ill|lt=Gyōki|Q1136664|WD=Q1136664|1=Gyōki}} petitioned and temple halls and shrine buildings were constructed. The site was later destroyed by war fire in the {{ill|lt=Ōnin|Q1143903|WD=Q1143903|1=Ōnin}} era, but in {{ill|lt=1595|Q6782|WD=Q6782|1=1595}} ({{ill|lt=Bunroku|Q1373039|WD=Q1373039|1=Bunroku}} 3) a two-by-four-bay shrine hall was rebuilt. In {{ill|lt=1600|Q6720|WD=Q6720|1=1600}} ({{ill|lt=Keichō|Q1328185|WD=Q1328185|1=Keichō}} 6), its thatched roof was repaired.<ref>{{Cite web|和書|url= http://kamnavi.jp/en/izumi/yamadai.htm |publisher=Kannabi|title=Yamadai Shrine|accessdate=2020-06-20}}</ref>. It was an Engishiki inner shrine and once had a temple-shrine of this sanctuary called Chōkō-ji, but was separated by {{ill|lt=shinbutsu bunri|Q1970535|WD=Q1970535|1=Shinbutsu bunri}}. In {{ill|lt=1872|Q7753|WD=Q7753|1=1872}} (Meiji 5) it was ranked {{ill|lt=village shrine|Q10444029|WD=Q10444029|lt=village shrine|1=Shakaku}}, and in Meiji 44 it merged Yaoyorozu Shrine and Kijima Shrine<ref>Local information signboard</ref>.

=== Enshrined deities ===
